# Next.js 15 App Router Best Practices

## Core Principles

- **DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)**: Extract reusable logic into utilities, hooks, and components
- **Server Components First**: Default to Server Components, only use Client Components when necessary
- **Type Safety**: Use TypeScript strict mode with explicit types
- **Performance**: Optimize requests with caching, parallel fetching, and streaming
- **Error Handling**: Implement comprehensive error boundaries and fallbacks

## Project Structure

```
app/
├── (auth)/                 # Route groups for auth pages
├── (dashboard)/            # Route groups for dashboard
├── api/                    # API routes
├── components/             # Reusable Server Components
├── lib/                    # Utilities and helpers
├── hooks/                  # Custom React hooks (Client Components)
├── types/                  # TypeScript type definitions
├── styles/                 # Global styles
└── ui/                     # UI components library

src/
├── app/                    # App Router pages and layouts
├── components/            # Shared components
└── lib/                    # Shared utilities
```

## TypeScript Configuration

- Use strict mode with `strict: true` in tsconfig.json
- Define explicit types for all props, functions, and return values
- Use interfaces over types for object shapes
- Use `Promise<T>` type for async functions
- Always type function parameters and return values

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Explicit types
interface WalletBalanceProps {
  address: string;
  chainId: number;
}

export async function getWalletBalance(
  address: string,
  chainId: number
): Promise<{ balance: string; symbol: string }> {
  // Implementation
}

// ❌ Bad: Implicit any
export async function getWalletBalance(address, chainId) {
  // Implementation
}
```

## Server Components (Default)

- **Always default to Server Components** unless interactivity is required
- Fetch data directly in Server Components using async/await
- Never use hooks (useState, useEffect, etc.) in Server Components
- Pass serializable data as props to Client Components

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Server Component fetching data
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';

export default async function WalletPage() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const token = cookieStore.get('token')?.value;
  
  const wallets = await fetchWallets(token);
  
  return (
    <div>
      {wallets.map(wallet => (
        <WalletCard key={wallet.id} wallet={wallet} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

// ❌ Bad: Using hooks in Server Component
export default function WalletPage() {
  const [wallets, setWallets] = useState([]);
  useEffect(() => {
    // ...
  }, []);
}
```

## Client Components (When Needed)

- Only use Client Components for:
  - Event handlers (onClick, onChange, etc.)
  - Browser APIs (localStorage, window, etc.)
  - State management (useState, useReducer)
  - Lifecycle effects (useEffect)
  - Custom hooks with state

- Add `'use client'` directive at the top of the file
- Keep Client Components as small as possible

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Minimal Client Component
'use client';

import { useState } from 'react';

interface ConnectWalletButtonProps {
  onConnect: (address: string) => void;
}

export function ConnectWalletButton({ onConnect }: ConnectWalletButtonProps) {
  const [isConnecting, setIsConnecting] = useState(false);
  
  const handleConnect = async () => {
    setIsConnecting(true);
    try {
      const address = await connectMetaMask();
      onConnect(address);
    } finally {
      setIsConnecting(false);
    }
  };
  
  return (
    <button onClick={handleConnect} disabled={isConnecting}>
      {isConnecting ? 'Connecting...' : 'Connect Wallet'}
    </button>
  );
}
```

## Data Fetching Patterns

### Parallel Data Fetching

- Start all fetches simultaneously, then await with Promise.all
- Use this pattern to avoid sequential waterfalls

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Parallel fetching
export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const [walletData, priceData, txHistory] = await Promise.all([
    getWalletData(),
    getPriceData(),
    getTransactionHistory(),
  ]);
  
  return <Dashboard wallet={walletData} prices={priceData} txs={txHistory} />;
}

// ❌ Bad: Sequential fetching
export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const walletData = await getWalletData();
  const priceData = await getPriceData();
  const txHistory = await getTransactionHistory();
  
  return <Dashboard wallet={walletData} prices={priceData} txs={txHistory} />;
}
```

### Caching and Revalidation

- Use `cache: 'force-cache'` for static data that rarely changes
- Use `cache: 'no-store'` for dynamic data
- Use `revalidate` option for time-based revalidation
- Use `revalidateTag` and `revalidatePath` for on-demand revalidation

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Cached fetch with revalidation
export async function getTokenPrices() {
  const res = await fetch('https://api.hyperevm.com/prices', {
    next: { revalidate: 60 }, // Revalidate every 60 seconds
  });
  
  return res.json();
}

// ✅ Good: On-demand revalidation
import { revalidateTag } from 'next/cache';

export async function updateWalletTag(walletId: string) {
  revalidateTag(`wallet-${walletId}`);
}
```

### Streaming with Suspense

- Use loading.tsx for route-level loading states
- Use Suspense boundaries for component-level streaming
- Provide meaningful loading states (skeletons, not spinners)

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Streaming with Suspense
import { Suspense } from 'react';

export default function WalletPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Wallet Overview</h1>
      <Suspense fallback={<WalletBalanceSkeleton />}>
        <WalletBalance />
      </Suspense>
      <Suspense fallback={<TransactionListSkeleton />}>
        <TransactionList />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Error Handling

- Create error.tsx files for route error boundaries
- Use try-catch blocks for critical operations
- Provide user-friendly error messages
- Log errors appropriately

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Error handling
export default async function WalletPage() {
  try {
    const wallet = await getWallet();
    return <WalletDetails wallet={wallet} />;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Failed to fetch wallet:', error);
    throw new Error('Unable to load wallet data');
  }
}

// error.tsx
'use client';

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Something went wrong!</h2>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Component Patterns

### Props Interface Pattern

- Always define interfaces for component props
- Use descriptive prop names
- Make props optional with `?` when appropriate

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Clear props interface
interface TokenCardProps {
  token: Token;
  showBalance?: boolean;
  onSelect?: (token: Token) => void;
}

export function TokenCard({ token, showBalance = true, onSelect }: TokenCardProps) {
  return (
    <div onClick={() => onSelect?.(token)}>
      <h3>{token.symbol}</h3>
      {showBalance && <p>{token.balance}</p>}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Composition Pattern

- Use children prop for flexible composition
- Prefer composition over configuration

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Composition pattern
interface WalletLayoutProps {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  sidebar?: React.ReactNode;
}

export function WalletLayout({ children, sidebar }: WalletLayoutProps) {
  return (
    <div className="flex">
      {sidebar && <aside>{sidebar}</aside>}
      <main>{children}</main>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Imports and Path Aliases

- Use absolute imports with `@/` alias
- Organize imports: external → internal → relative
- Use `import type` for type-only imports

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Organized imports
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

import { WalletCard } from '@/components/wallet-card';
import { getWalletData } from '@/lib/api';
import styles from './page.module.css';
```

## API Routes

- Place API routes in `app/api/` directory
- Export HTTP method functions (GET, POST, etc.)
- Use NextRequest and NextResponse
- Validate request data
- Return appropriate status codes

```typescript
// ✅ Good: API route
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import { z } from 'zod';

const createWalletSchema = z.object({
  address: z.string().regex(/^0x[a-fA-F0-9]{40}$/),
  chainId: z.number(),
});

export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  try {
    const body = await request.json();
    const data = createWalletSchema.parse(body);
    
    // Process request
    const wallet = await createWallet(data);
    
    return NextResponse.json(wallet, { status: 201 });
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof z.ZodError) {
      return NextResponse.json(
        { error: 'Invalid request data', details: error.errors },
        { status: 400 }
      );
    }
    
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: 'Internal server error' },
      { status: 500 }
    );
  }
}
```

## Performance Optimization

### Dynamic Imports

- Use dynamic imports for heavy components
- Use `ssr: false` for client-only components

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Dynamic import
import dynamic from 'next/dynamic';

const WalletChart = dynamic(() => import('@/components/wallet-chart'), {
  loading: () => <ChartSkeleton />,
  ssr: false,
});
```

### Image Optimization

- Always use next/image for images
- Provide width, height, and alt attributes
- Use priority for above-the-fold images

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Optimized image
import Image from 'next/image';

<Image
  src="/token-icon.png"
  alt="Token icon"
  width={64}
  height={64}
  priority
/>
```

## Environment Variables

- Use `.env.local` for local development
- Prefix public variables with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`
- Never expose secrets to the client
- Use `server-only` package to enforce server-only code

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Environment variables
import 'server-only';

const apiKey = process.env.HYPEREVM_API_KEY; // Server-only
const publicApiUrl = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL; // Available on client
```

## Async Patterns (Next.js 15+)

- All dynamic APIs are now async: cookies(), headers(), draftMode()
- Always await these APIs

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Async APIs in Next.js 15+
import { cookies, headers } from 'next/headers';

export default async function Page() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const headersList = await headers();
  
  const token = cookieStore.get('token')?.value;
  const userAgent = headersList.get('user-agent');
  
  return <div>...</div>;
}
```

## Testing

- Write tests for critical business logic
- Use vitest for unit tests
- Use Playwright for E2E tests
- Test components in isolation

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Component test
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import { WalletCard } from './wallet-card';

describe('WalletCard', () => {
  it('displays wallet address', () => {
    const wallet = { address: '0x123...', balance: '100' };
    render(<WalletCard wallet={wallet} />);
    
    expect(screen.getByText('0x123...')).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

